1
00:00:05,060 --> 00:00:10,635
So my name is Cole Worley and I'm the staff designer and sort of the de facto head of

2
00:00:10,675 --> 00:00:13,784
development at Leader Games, which is a small game studio.

3
00:00:14,716 --> 00:00:16,557
based in St. Paul, Minnesota.

4
00:00:16,657 --> 00:00:18,719
We have about seven people on staff,

5
00:00:19,499 --> 00:00:22,201
which is sort of like large for a small studio,

6
00:00:22,341 --> 00:00:24,542
but nowhere near what like an actual publisher

7
00:00:24,582 --> 00:00:25,123
would look like.

8
00:00:25,843 --> 00:00:27,624
We all still only work in one room.

9
00:00:28,445 --> 00:00:29,966
And over the past couple years,

10
00:00:29,986 --> 00:00:31,427
I have been working for them,

11
00:00:31,527 --> 00:00:33,388
and we have together have made the game Root,

12
00:00:33,988 --> 00:00:35,329
which I'll be talking a little bit today.

13
00:00:36,350 --> 00:00:37,431
And then in addition to that,

14
00:00:37,791 --> 00:00:39,552
I have a small micro publisher with my brother

15
00:00:39,592 --> 00:00:41,193
where we do sort of weird history games.

16
00:00:42,394 --> 00:00:44,254
I've been thinking about and designing games

17
00:00:44,794 --> 00:00:47,055
about conflict, about king-making,

18
00:00:47,555 --> 00:00:50,096
and about how uncomfortable it makes us feel for a while,

19
00:00:50,236 --> 00:00:51,916
and so I'm gonna kind of put those thoughts together.

20
00:00:52,596 --> 00:00:55,177
When I originally sat out to give this talk,

21
00:00:55,217 --> 00:00:57,477
I thought I'd start with something like a Root post-mortem.

22
00:00:58,138 --> 00:00:59,258
You know, this is a GDC talk,

23
00:00:59,318 --> 00:01:01,618
and people seem to like picking apart dead bodies,

24
00:01:02,159 --> 00:01:04,359
but Root, it still feels way too early for it.

25
00:01:04,859 --> 00:01:06,660
We have a big Kickstarter going on right now,

26
00:01:06,720 --> 00:01:08,260
there's lots of content coming down the pipe.

27
00:01:09,021 --> 00:01:14,768
And I just don't think I have a vantage point which I could think systematically about what

28
00:01:14,828 --> 00:01:16,790
Root is and what it's done well and not done well.

29
00:01:17,131 --> 00:01:19,914
Although if you do have questions about the creation, we can certainly talk about that

30
00:01:20,495 --> 00:01:21,175
in the Q&A.

31
00:01:22,237 --> 00:01:27,263
However, when I was thinking about this talk, as I dug into Root, I was reminded of the

32
00:01:27,323 --> 00:01:28,624
strangeness of the design.

33
00:01:29,681 --> 00:01:32,523
Now, for any of you who've sort of gone through

34
00:01:32,543 --> 00:01:33,944
all the paces with the big project,

35
00:01:33,964 --> 00:01:35,084
you know that by the end of the project,

36
00:01:35,124 --> 00:01:36,965
it seems like the most natural thing in the world.

37
00:01:37,666 --> 00:01:39,187
But with a little bit of distance,

38
00:01:39,227 --> 00:01:40,828
you can be reminded of how weird it is.

39
00:01:41,728 --> 00:01:44,530
Root is a strange game, and it's done well.

40
00:01:44,610 --> 00:01:46,471
Every year we'll kind of produce like a breakout hit.

41
00:01:47,151 --> 00:01:48,732
I just had never thought that anything

42
00:01:48,772 --> 00:01:49,753
I'd ever work on would do it.

43
00:01:49,813 --> 00:01:52,375
It just wasn't something that we were designing for.

44
00:01:52,755 --> 00:01:55,096
Now, I don't mean to sound ungrateful about any of this.

45
00:01:55,637 --> 00:01:57,578
Root was blessed with a wonderful creative team.

46
00:01:58,314 --> 00:01:59,254
and a great artist.

47
00:01:59,474 --> 00:02:01,195
These are some drawings from Kyle Fair

48
00:02:01,235 --> 00:02:02,455
and I just want to show off his talent

49
00:02:02,515 --> 00:02:03,916
because I get to bother him

50
00:02:03,996 --> 00:02:06,077
and fill out the art request list

51
00:02:06,297 --> 00:02:07,157
and I want to show it off.

52
00:02:08,658 --> 00:02:10,038
The game is cute, it's adorable,

53
00:02:10,178 --> 00:02:14,060
it pulls people in and it has a really nice pitch.

54
00:02:14,140 --> 00:02:16,361
So Root is an asymmetric strategy game.

55
00:02:17,081 --> 00:02:19,822
Now usually when we say an asymmetric strategy game,

56
00:02:20,452 --> 00:02:24,895
people tend to think about it on the order of different powers in a D&D party.

57
00:02:25,355 --> 00:02:30,820
One person's the tank, another person might be healing, someone's a magic user or a thief.

58
00:02:31,420 --> 00:02:37,145
Root's really asymmetric, so dramatically asymmetric that the different player positions

59
00:02:37,205 --> 00:02:40,427
are almost operating in different games.

60
00:02:41,368 --> 00:02:46,092
So as an example, the way the pitch goes, if I were encountering you guys at PAX East

61
00:02:46,152 --> 00:02:46,592
or something.

62
00:02:47,070 --> 00:02:49,392
It's basically one player is managing a kingdom.

63
00:02:49,912 --> 00:02:52,194
She starts the game with full control of the board,

64
00:02:52,214 --> 00:02:53,836
a warrior in nearly every clearing.

65
00:02:53,856 --> 00:02:55,437
There are buildings all over the place.

66
00:02:55,457 --> 00:02:57,299
She's freshly conquered the woodland.

67
00:02:57,859 --> 00:02:59,420
And all she needs to do is keep the peace.

68
00:03:00,361 --> 00:03:02,163
And she's keeping the peace so that she can move

69
00:03:02,183 --> 00:03:05,205
her resources around and build her kingdom up.

70
00:03:05,970 --> 00:03:09,091
And during that process, a rebellion might break out,

71
00:03:09,211 --> 00:03:11,773
and she might have to deal with sympathy for the insurgents.

72
00:03:12,573 --> 00:03:13,754
In order to put down the rebellion,

73
00:03:13,814 --> 00:03:17,016
she might find help from a wandering mercenary.

74
00:03:17,476 --> 00:03:19,457
But if the mercenary in putting down the rebellion

75
00:03:19,477 --> 00:03:20,918
becomes more popular than she is,

76
00:03:20,958 --> 00:03:23,419
then maybe she'll have to exile that mercenary.

77
00:03:24,460 --> 00:03:25,680
There's no script to this.

78
00:03:25,880 --> 00:03:27,841
All of these interactions happen organically.

79
00:03:28,061 --> 00:03:31,383
And rather than these different events

80
00:03:31,403 --> 00:03:34,025
sort of being dictated by a draw of an event card,

81
00:03:34,945 --> 00:03:37,887
Each one of these different positions is essentially a different player.

82
00:03:38,067 --> 00:03:44,451
One player plays, you know, essentially an adventure game working within the larger game.

83
00:03:44,551 --> 00:03:48,013
The player who's playing the rebellion is having to be really, is essentially playing

84
00:03:48,053 --> 00:03:53,356
a political game underneath the economic game that the Marquis de Cat is playing.

85
00:03:54,043 --> 00:03:55,965
Now usually around this time, if I'm at a convention,

86
00:03:55,985 --> 00:03:57,346
I'll turn around the box and they'll see

87
00:03:57,386 --> 00:03:58,507
these really cute meeples.

88
00:03:58,947 --> 00:04:00,628
And the thing is more or less sold on the spot

89
00:04:00,728 --> 00:04:02,209
because look at that meeple.

90
00:04:04,390 --> 00:04:06,452
But before I ring them up on the register,

91
00:04:06,772 --> 00:04:09,814
I have to be as straight as possible with them.

92
00:04:10,955 --> 00:04:13,116
Root is not a game for everybody.

93
00:04:14,137 --> 00:04:16,499
Usually the test I give to prospective buyers

94
00:04:16,639 --> 00:04:17,479
looks something like this.

95
00:04:19,111 --> 00:04:21,172
Are you okay with the fact that one of your friends

96
00:04:21,232 --> 00:04:22,613
is going to put pieces on the board,

97
00:04:23,053 --> 00:04:23,994
and then another one of your friends

98
00:04:24,054 --> 00:04:25,435
is going to remove those pieces,

99
00:04:26,215 --> 00:04:27,556
and they might laugh at you when they do it.

100
00:04:27,936 --> 00:04:29,277
And if you can pass that test,

101
00:04:29,537 --> 00:04:31,258
you're probably a good candidate to buying it.

102
00:04:32,218 --> 00:04:33,139
There's just no getting around it.

103
00:04:33,299 --> 00:04:34,479
The game is very, very mean.

104
00:04:35,640 --> 00:04:39,122
And it's mean in a way that is a little out of step

105
00:04:39,402 --> 00:04:42,403
with not only the kinds of games

106
00:04:42,543 --> 00:04:44,704
that sell to a broad audience in the hobby market,

107
00:04:45,045 --> 00:04:47,066
but also a more general design ethos.

108
00:04:48,459 --> 00:04:51,761
Now, it's mean, I think when we talk about the meanness,

109
00:04:51,801 --> 00:04:53,382
I should be specific what I'm talking about.

110
00:04:53,562 --> 00:04:54,703
There are no catch-up mechanisms.

111
00:04:55,364 --> 00:04:57,265
There's a lot of direct player interaction.

112
00:04:57,805 --> 00:04:58,846
Some of it is zero-sum.

113
00:04:59,326 --> 00:05:00,867
I'm gonna take something and you can't have it.

114
00:05:02,208 --> 00:05:05,390
It's also got a really, really high variance.

115
00:05:05,970 --> 00:05:08,812
Depending on the faction mixes, the play styles,

116
00:05:09,172 --> 00:05:11,973
all of the things around the actual playing of the game,

117
00:05:12,594 --> 00:05:14,995
a round of Root can look very, very, very different.

118
00:05:16,065 --> 00:05:18,506
and I don't want to hide that from the players.

119
00:05:19,306 --> 00:05:22,167
Now, usually these sorts of elements

120
00:05:22,207 --> 00:05:24,088
are kind of regarded as a little bit old-fashioned,

121
00:05:24,188 --> 00:05:26,289
and they get polished out in the development process.

122
00:05:26,449 --> 00:05:29,189
I've been fortunate to be on the development teams

123
00:05:29,209 --> 00:05:31,730
for many games, and I know that when a game

124
00:05:31,950 --> 00:05:36,672
goes from design to development, the questions shift, right?

125
00:05:36,772 --> 00:05:37,872
When you're designing a game,

126
00:05:37,952 --> 00:05:39,253
you're trying to make an impression.

127
00:05:39,877 --> 00:05:42,158
You're trying to capture the imagination

128
00:05:42,178 --> 00:05:43,359
of your prospective publisher.

129
00:05:44,039 --> 00:05:45,239
But when you're developing a game,

130
00:05:45,439 --> 00:05:46,740
you're trying to make sure that you're not

131
00:05:46,760 --> 00:05:47,860
gonna make your players mad.

132
00:05:49,001 --> 00:05:49,221
Right?

133
00:05:49,281 --> 00:05:51,822
I mean, it's a wholly different set of skills.

134
00:05:52,142 --> 00:05:53,223
You don't wanna make your players mad.

135
00:05:53,243 --> 00:05:54,823
You want them to come back, to like it.

136
00:05:55,403 --> 00:05:57,784
You don't want hate mail on BGG

137
00:05:57,864 --> 00:05:59,185
or really angry Reddit threads.

138
00:06:01,402 --> 00:06:04,784
So when Root started moving from design to development,

139
00:06:04,824 --> 00:06:06,265
I was a little worried because of the things

140
00:06:06,285 --> 00:06:07,765
that I really liked about the game

141
00:06:07,805 --> 00:06:08,906
were the things that I knew

142
00:06:09,566 --> 00:06:11,667
were going to be totally destroyed in development.

143
00:06:12,327 --> 00:06:14,989
Thankfully, Patrick Leder, our owner and creative director,

144
00:06:15,029 --> 00:06:17,670
had the temerity to also let me be on the development team,

145
00:06:18,410 --> 00:06:20,151
and which is an awful decision.

146
00:06:20,892 --> 00:06:22,853
You should never allow a designer to work on development.

147
00:06:23,113 --> 00:06:24,053
I really love development,

148
00:06:24,133 --> 00:06:26,754
and I love the process of cutting something apart

149
00:06:26,794 --> 00:06:28,115
that I've spent a year building.

150
00:06:29,286 --> 00:06:32,228
But I worked really hard to make sure that even as we made

151
00:06:32,268 --> 00:06:35,109
the game more elegant and as we sort of cut it up nicely,

152
00:06:35,489 --> 00:06:38,010
that the weird parts were the parts that stayed.

153
00:06:38,930 --> 00:06:41,191
So, today I want to talk a little bit about

154
00:06:41,432 --> 00:06:44,393
the sharp edges of root, the meanness of the game.

155
00:06:45,553 --> 00:06:50,556
And I want to do this not by talking about root,

156
00:06:50,616 --> 00:06:53,417
but instead by talking about why we think of those things

157
00:06:53,477 --> 00:06:55,058
as sharp edges in the first place,

158
00:06:55,338 --> 00:06:58,359
and what we might be losing when we don't explore them.

159
00:06:59,180 --> 00:07:04,883
And so in order to sort of launch this exploration, I think we have to think about a sort of central term,

160
00:07:04,923 --> 00:07:07,385
and that term for me is kingmaking.

161
00:07:08,005 --> 00:07:10,507
Because ultimately, Root is a game about kingmaking.

162
00:07:10,527 --> 00:07:13,509
I always have a good laugh when I see a thread and someone's like,

163
00:07:13,569 --> 00:07:16,310
oh man, Root, I heard that it has a kingmaking problem.

164
00:07:16,330 --> 00:07:19,192
And I'm like, it doesn't have a kingmaking problem, it is the kingmaking problem.

165
00:07:20,579 --> 00:07:21,639
And it's a political game.

166
00:07:21,659 --> 00:07:23,340
I mean, if you're making a political game,

167
00:07:23,560 --> 00:07:25,861
it makes sense that you're dealing with concepts

168
00:07:25,881 --> 00:07:27,181
like power brokers, right?

169
00:07:28,062 --> 00:07:30,543
But the fact that we oftentimes get friction there

170
00:07:30,703 --> 00:07:33,084
from people wanting to buy the game or from critics,

171
00:07:33,524 --> 00:07:38,006
I think suggests that we are currently in a tabletop era

172
00:07:38,406 --> 00:07:41,067
that is really locked into a certain kind of design ethos.

173
00:07:41,939 --> 00:07:45,821
So we're going to start by talking a little bit about kingmaking and I'm going to try to trace

174
00:07:45,901 --> 00:07:51,544
why I think it's fallen out of fashion and then I want to marshal a sort of like simple defense

175
00:07:51,584 --> 00:07:56,327
for kingmaking and then talk about some practical lessons for those would-be practitioners out there.

176
00:07:57,134 --> 00:07:57,975
So, king making.

177
00:07:58,255 --> 00:08:00,217
The act of making someone king, it's pretty simple.

178
00:08:00,497 --> 00:08:02,638
The term is actually a little bit more interesting than that.

179
00:08:03,419 --> 00:08:05,120
It starts with this guy, there he is,

180
00:08:05,260 --> 00:08:06,661
Richard Neville, Earl Warwick.

181
00:08:06,922 --> 00:08:08,983
By the way, you're gonna get a lot of stupid,

182
00:08:09,083 --> 00:08:11,805
no animation PowerPoints from me with old pictures

183
00:08:12,326 --> 00:08:13,847
because I come from an academic background

184
00:08:13,927 --> 00:08:15,268
and that's how we do our PowerPoints.

185
00:08:16,169 --> 00:08:21,294
So this guy Richard Neville, the Earl of Warwick, Warwick the Kingmaker he was called during the War of the Roses,

186
00:08:22,275 --> 00:08:26,940
that title was used almost entirely derisively because he was, you know,

187
00:08:26,980 --> 00:08:33,307
back, you know, we're back in the era of the divine right of kings. If you have someone, a human, deciding who to become king,

188
00:08:33,367 --> 00:08:35,750
that's an awful heretical idea.

189
00:08:36,962 --> 00:08:40,624
And so it falls out of fashion pretty quickly, although, and just a little note,

190
00:08:40,844 --> 00:08:43,605
so the game on the right is Avalon Hill's famous game Kingmaker,

191
00:08:44,546 --> 00:08:47,107
which I always thought was named after, like, the kingmaking problem,

192
00:08:47,127 --> 00:08:50,748
but it's actually, no, it's about Mr. Earl of Warwick over there.

193
00:08:51,969 --> 00:08:55,731
Now, an interesting thing happens in the 18th century, so a few hundred years after that,

194
00:08:56,351 --> 00:08:57,651
the historian David Hume...

195
00:08:58,955 --> 00:09:01,457
You didn't think I was going to go there, but here we are in the 18th century.

196
00:09:01,877 --> 00:09:04,638
He starts using the word kingmaker in a very positive way.

197
00:09:04,658 --> 00:09:10,801
He loves Richard Neville because for him, to be master of your age was to be in a position

198
00:09:10,901 --> 00:09:12,842
where you got to determine the course of history.

199
00:09:13,322 --> 00:09:16,524
And so the kingmakers are the real heroes, not the kings.

200
00:09:16,544 --> 00:09:17,864
So

201
00:09:20,300 --> 00:09:23,104
Here a slight bit of disclosure is needed.

202
00:09:23,464 --> 00:09:26,147
I love games when I get to make the king,

203
00:09:26,388 --> 00:09:27,449
even if I don't get to be the king.

204
00:09:27,969 --> 00:09:31,233
And oftentimes I even enjoy the experience

205
00:09:31,694 --> 00:09:32,995
when it fires against me.

206
00:09:33,396 --> 00:09:35,558
When I was sort of looking for pictures

207
00:09:35,698 --> 00:09:37,581
deep, deep, deep inside of Board Game Geek,

208
00:09:37,701 --> 00:09:38,682
I stumbled into this one.

209
00:09:39,279 --> 00:09:41,500
Circa 2006 in the Twilight Imperium.

210
00:09:42,941 --> 00:09:44,743
It's in the Twilight Imperium image gallery, guys.

211
00:09:45,383 --> 00:09:48,906
And this is a rare shot of me playing a game of Twilight

212
00:09:48,926 --> 00:09:51,948
Imperium at the moment someone has stolen the victory for me

213
00:09:51,988 --> 00:09:53,530
by passing an idiotic law.

214
00:09:55,331 --> 00:09:56,092
And I just.

215
00:09:57,067 --> 00:09:58,067
There's hatred in those eyes.

216
00:09:58,128 --> 00:10:00,990
But also, that's a game that stuck in my mind.

217
00:10:01,010 --> 00:10:02,131
When I stumbled on this picture,

218
00:10:02,151 --> 00:10:03,371
which I had completely forgotten about,

219
00:10:04,052 --> 00:10:06,354
I remembered so many things about that game,

220
00:10:06,394 --> 00:10:07,675
including the fact that we were playing

221
00:10:08,295 --> 00:10:10,797
in a weird, like, attic-y space,

222
00:10:10,857 --> 00:10:12,638
and we only had three hours to play.

223
00:10:12,658 --> 00:10:14,480
So we played a game of Twilight Imperium in three hours,

224
00:10:14,600 --> 00:10:15,681
if you can possibly believe it.

225
00:10:17,442 --> 00:10:17,542
So.

226
00:10:19,458 --> 00:10:25,260
Even talking about kingmaking and thinking about the idea that it might be desirable

227
00:10:25,320 --> 00:10:30,482
for you to steal a victory from your friend and to be mean to each other, it provokes

228
00:10:30,583 --> 00:10:34,344
even me, a fan of the genre, it provokes a really physical response.

229
00:10:34,744 --> 00:10:36,405
My stomach turns a little and I cringe.

230
00:10:37,826 --> 00:10:41,887
This is strange because we all have opinions about games.

231
00:10:41,927 --> 00:10:45,669
You might like party games or you might like games about Panzer tanks in World War II.

232
00:10:46,400 --> 00:10:49,661
But your distaste for panzer takes doesn't lead you

233
00:10:49,741 --> 00:10:50,961
to have your stomach turn.

234
00:10:51,621 --> 00:10:52,682
King-making, on the other hand,

235
00:10:52,802 --> 00:10:54,562
is attacking something really basic.

236
00:10:54,742 --> 00:10:58,344
And as someone who plays games and designs them

237
00:10:58,384 --> 00:11:00,744
and also tries to really earnestly study them,

238
00:11:01,265 --> 00:11:03,065
that physical response is interesting

239
00:11:03,305 --> 00:11:06,826
because it seems different from other ways of,

240
00:11:08,007 --> 00:11:10,608
other preferences that we express about our games.

241
00:11:12,508 --> 00:11:12,668
So.

242
00:11:14,541 --> 00:11:16,202
Why do we dislike kingmaking so much?

243
00:11:16,262 --> 00:11:17,662
Where does this dislike come from?

244
00:11:18,023 --> 00:11:18,903
Was it always with us?

245
00:11:19,043 --> 00:11:21,004
Is this sort of a new invention?

246
00:11:21,124 --> 00:11:24,086
I sort of want to start here with this really, really broad

247
00:11:24,686 --> 00:11:25,627
historical frame.

248
00:11:25,707 --> 00:11:29,649
Because I think one thing that happens when we talk about

249
00:11:29,689 --> 00:11:31,530
