00:23:54,859 --> 00:23:57,020
were convinced in the desirability of games,

492
00:23:57,121 --> 00:23:59,422
especially team games in training the young.

493
00:23:59,562 --> 00:24:00,423
This is a quote from him.

494
00:24:00,803 --> 00:24:02,284
They believed in the value of those games

495
00:24:02,304 --> 00:24:03,966
for the development of ethical behavior.

496
00:24:04,366 --> 00:24:07,569
They had a view of education that was not only national, but also imperial.

497
00:24:07,930 --> 00:24:10,753
They saw it as their duty to give a lead to the imperial world.

498
00:24:11,193 --> 00:24:14,837
So all these schools start spreading throughout India, and they're having Indian cricket teams,

499
00:24:14,897 --> 00:24:17,440
and all the best teams in cricket these days are Indian teams.

500
00:24:17,880 --> 00:24:23,206
But it was part of the civilizing mission to sort of teach fairness, and to teach rules

501
00:24:23,466 --> 00:24:23,886
and law.

502
00:24:25,362 --> 00:24:30,143
because all of those things reflected the sort of ideological program of the British state.

503
00:24:30,763 --> 00:24:33,724
Now, this can seem a little distant from us, right?

504
00:24:33,784 --> 00:24:38,545
Here we are in San Francisco, GDC, and we are so, so very far from the imperial program.

505
00:24:38,905 --> 00:24:47,048
But what you should know is that this tradition is still very much with us,

506
00:24:47,108 --> 00:24:50,329
and many of you guys are somewhat indoctrinated into it, including myself.

507
00:24:50,429 --> 00:24:51,729
I'm sorry to break your bubble.

508
00:24:52,149 --> 00:24:56,591
So rugby, we know, the game of rugby, it comes in name from the rugby school.

509
00:24:57,051 --> 00:25:03,035
It spawned a whole genre of novels called the British boarding school genre, including

510
00:25:03,055 --> 00:25:07,538
a novel called Tom Brown's School Days, which was the blue point for Harry Potter, of course.

511
00:25:08,979 --> 00:25:11,080
Harry Potter is an English boarding school drama.

512
00:25:11,280 --> 00:25:16,063
He's learning right now how to be a good little imperial servant, even though he doesn't think

513
00:25:16,083 --> 00:25:16,923
of himself that way.

514
00:25:17,244 --> 00:25:19,825
But if you get good at Quidditch, you'll get good at Empire.

515
00:25:21,439 --> 00:25:25,803
Now, the point of all this is not to suggest that fairness is wrong and that sports don't

516
00:25:25,843 --> 00:25:29,066
teach you good things about being a person and existing in society.

517
00:25:29,846 --> 00:25:34,671
It's just that I think that we have a lot to gain from giving ourselves a little bit

518
00:25:34,711 --> 00:25:38,074
of distance from the concept and for starting to imagine.

519
00:25:40,219 --> 00:25:46,567
Or maybe not imagine, but starting to treat the history of fairness as storied, right?

520
00:25:46,847 --> 00:25:53,976
If you are shooting for fairness in a design you're working on, you're making a kind of value judgment.

521
00:25:54,096 --> 00:25:56,820
And you should just keep that in mind as you're peddling your design.

522
00:25:57,380 --> 00:25:58,582
So what happens then?

523
00:25:59,483 --> 00:26:02,706
if we look for a different framework to design from?

524
00:26:03,306 --> 00:26:05,628
Maybe not an overall rejection of fairness,

525
00:26:05,908 --> 00:26:08,250
but just downgrading its value.

526
00:26:08,770 --> 00:26:12,553
Suddenly things like spite and being mean for no reason,

527
00:26:12,613 --> 00:26:15,296
like what if those are able to do something?

528
00:26:17,197 --> 00:26:19,399
Well, I think when you boil everything away,

529
00:26:20,938 --> 00:26:24,121
This shift in design priorities leads fundamentally

530
00:26:24,261 --> 00:26:28,264
to games where the winner is decided by a cabal

531
00:26:28,584 --> 00:26:31,246
rather than some sense of individual merit.

532
00:26:32,047 --> 00:26:34,128
In other words, we're talking about kingmaking.

533
00:26:35,249 --> 00:26:37,031
This, of course, being an old cover

534
00:26:37,071 --> 00:26:38,892
of the excellent, excellent game Diplomacy.

535
00:26:41,310 --> 00:26:47,713
So I want to tell you now and just offer a short defense of kingmaking as a concept and

536
00:26:47,773 --> 00:26:52,175
how we can go about that defense and then I'll talk about some design takeaways and

537
00:26:52,215 --> 00:26:54,516
sort of like practical tips for it.

538
00:26:55,056 --> 00:26:58,677
So I want to build this defense first on narrative grounds.

539
00:26:59,720 --> 00:27:03,322
Because I think that games are fundamentally a storytelling medium.

540
00:27:03,822 --> 00:27:08,103
Even when we're talking about games like The Estates or Chicago Express

541
00:27:08,183 --> 00:27:10,624
or some nerdy train game that has a spreadsheet in it,

542
00:27:12,065 --> 00:27:15,446
the biggest math fest game is still a storytelling game.

543
00:27:15,526 --> 00:27:17,507
It's communicating a kind of narrative.

544
00:27:18,067 --> 00:27:20,988
And so the critical language that we use to talk about stories

545
00:27:21,128 --> 00:27:23,369
is just well appointed to talk about games.

546
00:27:24,249 --> 00:27:25,090
In this sense...

547
00:27:26,217 --> 00:27:29,939
I think that we can talk about games in terms of cliché.

548
00:27:30,779 --> 00:27:35,300
So we know, for instance, that in romantic comedies, or comedies more general in the

549
00:27:35,340 --> 00:27:37,281
classic sense, that they're going to end in a marriage.

550
00:27:39,042 --> 00:27:40,762
That's a narrative cliché.

551
00:27:41,383 --> 00:27:45,824
Likewise, you know that when you're done playing an empire builder that everything that you

552
00:27:45,844 --> 00:27:50,506
did is going to cash out in really neat sets of three to one, like gold to victory point.

553
00:27:50,967 --> 00:27:53,908
Because we've got to tighten those scores somehow and make everybody feel like they

554
00:27:53,928 --> 00:27:57,389
were close to the end of the game, even though it was no contest at all.

555
00:27:59,590 --> 00:28:04,892
And these clichés can be frustrating because I'm sure you've had the thought watching a

556
00:28:04,912 --> 00:28:07,993
romantic comedy that it would have been much better if she would have left him at the end

557
00:28:08,013 --> 00:28:10,735
of the first act and the movie would have been much more interesting if she had just

558
00:28:10,755 --> 00:28:11,495
gone on a road trip.

559
00:28:12,275 --> 00:28:17,237
But the song and dance of going through the building of an engine and its scoring.

560
00:28:18,119 --> 00:28:21,022
is it's circumscribing the possible expression.

561
00:28:21,082 --> 00:28:22,984
And again, and I'll say this several more times,

562
00:28:23,304 --> 00:28:25,086
this isn't to suggest that those games are wrong.

563
00:28:25,106 --> 00:28:27,468
I love both of these games, especially Race.

564
00:28:28,529 --> 00:28:30,771
And I think that they are worth designing, playing,

565
00:28:30,791 --> 00:28:33,173
and there's still a lot of room to explore there.

566
00:28:33,253 --> 00:28:36,255
But we shouldn't allow that kind of genre

567
00:28:36,295 --> 00:28:39,458
to dominate our larger thinking about games.

568
00:28:41,366 --> 00:28:45,330
Kingmaking, in this sense, offers an alternative type

569
00:28:45,390 --> 00:28:46,791
of storytelling.

570
00:28:47,011 --> 00:28:49,674
It allows designers and players to tap

571
00:28:49,714 --> 00:28:53,758
into a really long tradition of betrayal and manipulation

572
00:28:53,818 --> 00:28:55,380
that's as old as narrative itself.

573
00:28:55,500 --> 00:28:57,682
And it forms the foundation for a lot of media

574
00:28:57,702 --> 00:29:00,445
that we enjoy today, from The Bachelor to Game of Thrones.

575
00:29:01,165 --> 00:29:03,568
And there's no reason why we shouldn't

576
00:29:03,628 --> 00:29:04,929
play with those concepts.

577
00:29:07,255 --> 00:29:13,280
When we talk about the engine builder, the primary sort of motif is construction.

578
00:29:13,320 --> 00:29:14,061
It's progressive.

579
00:29:15,282 --> 00:29:24,369
I won't go into Whig history because I'll bore you guys all to death, but what Kingmaking

580
00:29:24,510 --> 00:29:29,294
offers us is perhaps the most powerful narrative tool that any writer has ever used, which

581
00:29:29,354 --> 00:29:31,035
is to say it allows you to use irony.

582
00:29:31,792 --> 00:29:35,775
It allows you to tell a story of revenge and redemption without worrying that everyone's

583
00:29:35,795 --> 00:29:37,356
going to feel that they were fairly treated.

584
00:29:37,376 --> 00:29:39,598
It just opens up the kind of stories that you can tell.

585
00:29:40,219 --> 00:29:42,080
Now a quick sidebar to note that

586
00:29:42,703 --> 00:29:45,764
One space in games that has been really exploring this area

587
00:29:45,944 --> 00:29:47,924
is the single session RPG.

588
00:29:48,964 --> 00:29:50,085
There's a lot of interesting work

589
00:29:50,125 --> 00:29:52,025
happening with independent RPG makers

590
00:29:52,165 --> 00:29:54,186
that it's well worth viewing.

591
00:29:54,226 --> 00:29:55,986
And even if playing D&D makes you

592
00:29:56,006 --> 00:29:57,567
self-conscious or uncomfortable, you

593
00:29:57,587 --> 00:29:59,187
should buy some of the books I'm going

594
00:29:59,207 --> 00:30:00,607
to mention here in a second, because they

595
00:30:00,647 --> 00:30:01,928
are very, very interesting.

596
00:30:02,375 --> 00:30:04,657
just from their formal perspective.

597
00:30:04,977 --> 00:30:07,840
And here I'm thinking about Avery Adler's The Quiet Year

598
00:30:07,940 --> 00:30:09,681
and all of the rest of the games she's produced.

599
00:30:10,442 --> 00:30:13,885
And a game by a company called Thorny Games called Dialect.

600
00:30:14,705 --> 00:30:15,926
These are games that really upset

601
00:30:16,767 --> 00:30:18,248
what you might think is even possible

602
00:30:18,268 --> 00:30:19,109
in the space of a game.

603
00:30:19,129 --> 00:30:20,050
And even if you don't play them,

604
00:30:20,070 --> 00:30:21,951
the rules are powerful enough.

605
00:30:23,853 --> 00:30:27,055
Okay, so if we are going to build games about

606
00:30:28,174 --> 00:30:30,255
kingmaking, we need a different framework.

607
00:30:30,495 --> 00:30:32,275
We can't use fairness as the bedrock

608
00:30:32,635 --> 00:30:34,055
to build our design practice on.

609
00:30:34,095 --> 00:30:35,015
We have to find something else.

610
00:30:36,036 --> 00:30:36,816
So what do we find?

611
00:30:37,376 --> 00:30:40,997
Well, some people would jump to this gentleman over here,

612
00:30:41,017 --> 00:30:44,477
Renier Kinizia, who has made a few games.

613
00:30:45,138 --> 00:30:46,938
And he has this quote that you will see

614
00:30:46,978 --> 00:30:48,478
like tacked onto profiles.

615
00:30:49,619 --> 00:30:50,559
And I'll just, I'll read it here.

616
00:30:50,599 --> 00:30:51,959
When playing a game, the goal is to win.

617
00:30:52,670 --> 00:30:55,232
But it is the goal that is important, not the winning.

618
00:30:55,652 --> 00:30:57,453
This is a little bit like the old canard

619
00:30:57,594 --> 00:31:01,256
about the journey being more important than the destination.

620
00:31:01,716 --> 00:31:02,196
And it's fine.

621
00:31:03,926 --> 00:31:07,309
The main problem with it is it's relentlessly individualistic.

622
00:31:08,110 --> 00:31:10,692
It's about your personal experience of encountering the game,

623
00:31:11,073 --> 00:31:13,215
which I think, while that's a nice thought,

624
00:31:13,335 --> 00:31:16,978
it doesn't get into what makes something like Kingmaking so difficult,

625
00:31:17,038 --> 00:31:20,482
which is to say that my personal journey is going to intersect with yours,

626
00:31:20,962 --> 00:31:23,665
and one of us is going to rob the other and continue the journey.

627
00:31:24,232 --> 00:31:31,394
So, in sort of searching for a new framework, I found myself reaching for Bernie DeKoven's

628
00:31:31,494 --> 00:31:39,017
amazing 1978 book, The Well-Played Game, which I think is just an unbelievable text and one

629
00:31:39,037 --> 00:31:41,318
that anybody interested in design should check out.

630
00:31:41,418 --> 00:31:45,620
And in Bernie DeKoven's book, he has this really wonderful distinction he makes between

631
00:31:45,700 --> 00:31:47,400
playing to win and having to win.

632
00:31:48,161 --> 00:31:50,142
And there's a way that...

633
00:31:51,698 --> 00:31:55,405
This could be described simply as like another version of what Kinesia is talking about,

634
00:31:55,746 --> 00:31:58,812
but for De Koven, it has nothing to do with individual experience.

635
00:31:59,694 --> 00:32:01,978
Basically, when you play to win, you must win.

636
00:32:03,136 --> 00:32:04,876
Okay, cool. Everyone's always playing to win.

637
00:32:05,417 --> 00:32:08,678
But when you have to win, you must win because

638
00:32:09,258 --> 00:32:12,259
you are unsure of your own position in the community of players.

639
00:32:12,679 --> 00:32:15,700
And only by winning can you kind of prove yourself in that position.

640
00:32:16,200 --> 00:32:18,220
So basically, you know, if you think about

641
00:32:18,761 --> 00:32:22,002
all of the theory around the magic circle and the exceptional space of the game...

642
00:32:23,398 --> 00:32:29,101
What DeKoven is talking about is if you don't close that circle entirely and you bring in

643
00:32:29,161 --> 00:32:32,643
some of the outside world into your game, you're going to get people who are going to

644
00:32:32,683 --> 00:32:36,785
try to use the game as a way to manipulate the world outside of the game and that's where

645
00:32:36,805 --> 00:32:38,025
all the bad feelings come from.

646
00:32:40,342 --> 00:32:42,363
So he has a short note on this.

647
00:32:42,383 --> 00:32:44,284
I'm just going to, I didn't put this up,

648
00:32:44,545 --> 00:32:47,426
but I think for those of you who are interested in DeKoven's

649
00:32:47,466 --> 00:32:49,047
work, it can all be pretty much summed up

650
00:32:49,087 --> 00:32:50,708
in this kind of short little snippet.

651
00:32:51,428 --> 00:32:53,570
He describes games in this way.

652
00:32:53,590 --> 00:32:54,290
This is a quote.

653
00:32:55,070 --> 00:32:56,011
We were willing to play.

654
00:32:56,171 --> 00:32:58,052
We were each willing to play the particular game.

655
00:32:58,392 --> 00:32:59,473
We were willing to play with each other.

656
00:32:59,493 --> 00:33:01,594
And we arrived at the well-played game

657
00:33:01,814 --> 00:33:03,575
because of the way we combined with the game.

658
00:33:04,319 --> 00:33:07,682
Now, that's a little like woo-woo by today's standards,

659
00:33:07,742 --> 00:33:10,044
and know that if you do buy a copy of The Well-Played Game,

660
00:33:10,264 --> 00:33:12,567
an excellent book, it's entirely like that.

661
00:33:12,707 --> 00:33:14,709
It's like a giant stream of consciousness,

662
00:33:15,590 --> 00:33:16,651
exploration of play.

663
00:33:18,012 --> 00:33:20,855
But I think what is so powerful about DeKoven's idea is

664
00:33:20,875 --> 00:33:20,995
to

665
00:33:23,288 --> 00:33:25,990
back out from the individual instance of the game

666
00:33:26,090 --> 00:33:28,613
and to really reassert the power of play

667
00:33:29,033 --> 00:33:31,475
as the thing that the game is allowing you to do.

668
00:33:31,856 --> 00:33:34,298
The game is the medium that allows players

669
00:33:34,358 --> 00:33:35,479
to interact with each other.

670
00:33:36,240 --> 00:33:39,142
And if you are having the perfect experience of play,

671
00:33:39,543 --> 00:33:42,285
the victory is putting everybody on the same page,

672
00:33:42,665 --> 00:33:44,187
but it doesn't necessarily have to be the thing

673
00:33:44,407 --> 00:33:45,488
that is keeping them there.

674
00:33:47,049 --> 00:33:48,931
So, thinking about.

675
00:33:50,021 --> 00:33:51,321
as a foundation for kingmaking,

676
00:33:51,581 --> 00:33:53,582
I want to talk a little bit about some takeaways.

677
00:33:53,982 --> 00:33:55,342
What are some things that we can do

678
00:33:55,663 --> 00:33:56,983
with this alternate framework?

679
00:33:57,083 --> 00:34:00,104
A framework that doesn't overly emphasize fairness.

680
00:34:00,924 --> 00:34:03,105
Well, I think that I have a kind of set of rules

681
00:34:03,145 --> 00:34:04,686
that I think about when I'm working on a design,

682
00:34:04,746 --> 00:34:06,326
especially a design that I know

683
00:34:06,386 --> 00:34:07,907
is going to feature a lot of kingmaking.

684
00:34:08,987 --> 00:34:10,948
The first rule is that, as in all things,

685
00:34:11,048 --> 00:34:12,749
consent is absolutely critical.

686
00:34:13,089 --> 00:34:15,109
You do not want to misdirect your players.

687
00:34:15,230 --> 00:34:17,350
It's really important that everybody realizes

688
00:34:17,530 --> 00:34:19,051
what kind of game they're going to play.

689
00:34:21,129 --> 00:34:24,170
Dukovin has an interesting chapter in the well-played game where he talks about something

690
00:34:24,190 --> 00:34:25,370
called the dangerous game.

691
00:34:26,130 --> 00:34:32,833
And he notes in this chapter that dangerous games cannot involve people who haven't accepted

692
00:34:32,873 --> 00:34:35,674
the threat or haven't chosen to play the dangerous game.

693
00:34:36,174 --> 00:34:39,475
Now, this is a really interesting kind of two-tiered view of this.

694
00:34:39,835 --> 00:34:41,496
It's a little bit like watching a horror movie.

695
00:34:41,936 --> 00:34:45,657
You obviously would never want to watch a horror movie with somebody who hates horror

696
00:34:45,697 --> 00:34:45,997
movies.

697
00:34:47,695 --> 00:34:48,855
And so that's obviously bad.

698
00:34:49,255 --> 00:34:51,757
But what is less obviously bad, but what is still bad,

699
00:34:51,877 --> 00:34:53,958
is watching a horror movie where half the people

700
00:34:53,998 --> 00:34:55,418
like watching it because they think it's funny,

701
00:34:55,979 --> 00:34:57,559
and the other half the people like watching it

702
00:34:57,599 --> 00:34:58,720
because they think it's scary.

703
00:34:59,220 --> 00:35:03,482
Each of those, that heterogeneity and that viewing base

704
00:35:04,002 --> 00:35:05,663
really can hurt an experience.

705
00:35:05,723 --> 00:35:07,024
And so for DeKoven, it's important,

706
00:35:07,044 --> 00:35:08,365
if you want to play a dangerous game,

707
00:35:09,125 --> 00:35:11,386
to agree to play it, but then also to accept the danger.

708
00:35:12,367 --> 00:35:14,468
So, you should be honest about it.

709
00:35:14,548 --> 00:35:14,668
Now,

710
00:35:16,264 --> 00:35:20,729
It's also important to realize that if you are designing a game about king making,

711
00:35:20,869 --> 00:35:23,632
that the relationships between the players, that's everything.

712
00:35:24,112 --> 00:35:27,636
Mechanisms do not matter so much as the relationships to the player,

713
00:35:27,656 --> 00:35:30,799
and this is a very easy thing to forget when you're working in design.

714
00:35:32,160 --> 00:35:38,747
What will happen sometimes is when the relationships between the players are not highlighted,

715
00:35:39,430 --> 00:35:41,533
the interactions, the king-making interaction

716
00:35:41,553 --> 00:35:44,338
in the last stage of the game can feel like a cruel joke.

717
00:35:44,398 --> 00:35:46,521
If I've been hoarding stone the entire game

718
00:35:46,561 --> 00:35:47,923
so I can upgrade my clay house,

719
00:35:48,363 --> 00:35:50,126
and you take it from me in the last turn

720
00:35:50,166 --> 00:35:52,329
despite never touching me the entire game,

721
00:35:52,690 --> 00:35:53,751
it's not going to feel like

722
00:35:54,512 --> 00:35:57,153
an ironic coup or something worth thinking about.

723
00:35:57,413 --> 00:35:58,794
It's just going to feel like a bad joke.

724
00:35:59,274 --> 00:36:01,114
And this, I think, brings me to Risk,

725
00:36:01,174 --> 00:36:03,855
which I think is still just a brilliant and wonderful game.

726
00:36:04,256 --> 00:36:06,376
Maybe more fun to think about than to play.

727
00:36:06,796 --> 00:36:08,597
But one of the real tricks of Risk

728
00:36:08,677 --> 00:36:10,418
is that there's no negative space on the board.

729
00:36:10,958 --> 00:36:12,978
So what kind of game are you playing when you play Risk?

730
00:36:13,079 --> 00:36:14,819
Well, it's a game where you're going to hurt each other,

731
00:36:14,899 --> 00:36:16,100
and there's no way to get around it.

732
00:36:17,078 --> 00:36:21,659
I often wonder, a lot of space 4X games have this problem where the first third of the

733
00:36:21,699 --> 00:36:26,381
game is very quiet and it's about synergies and building up, and then in the second half

734
00:36:26,401 --> 00:36:29,862
you tear down all the work you did in the first half, and it usually makes people feel

735
00:36:29,962 --> 00:36:30,302
rotten.

736
00:36:30,642 --> 00:36:33,983
And I think if the board started full, you would get around this problem.

737
00:36:34,423 --> 00:36:35,644
This is one reason, by the way, in Root...

738
00:36:36,845 --> 00:36:38,406
the board starts completely full.

739
00:36:38,987 --> 00:36:41,428
And the primary aggressor in the game,

740
00:36:42,389 --> 00:36:43,910
the faction called the Eerie Dynasties,

741
00:36:44,210 --> 00:36:45,531
they're playing a program game

742
00:36:45,911 --> 00:36:48,973
where they are literally having to program in attacks

743
00:36:49,433 --> 00:36:50,854
so that they have sort of deniability.

744
00:36:50,874 --> 00:36:52,295
They're like, I didn't mean to attack you.

745
00:36:52,715 --> 00:36:54,637
It's just that's what I promised I would do

746
00:36:54,677 --> 00:36:55,497
for the rest of the game.

747
00:36:57,810 --> 00:37:01,192
So another note about this is,

748
00:37:02,092 --> 00:37:06,695
another interesting line about that kind of thematic

749
00:37:06,735 --> 00:37:09,196
and mechanical cohesion is a comparison

750
00:37:09,216 --> 00:37:11,257
between something like Inish and Blood Rage.

751
00:37:11,857 --> 00:37:14,058
So these are both like, if you look at just the boxes

752
00:37:14,098 --> 00:37:15,679
and the pieces, you're like, oh yeah,

753
00:37:15,699 --> 00:37:17,460
there's some war happening in these boxes.

754
00:37:18,560 --> 00:37:20,361
In Inish, you fight all the time.

755
00:37:20,817 --> 00:37:21,678
Oh, it's a fighting game.

756
00:37:21,798 --> 00:37:22,738
It's a very fighting game.

757
00:37:23,039 --> 00:37:25,280
But Blood Rage is really more of like a drafting game.

758
00:37:25,320 --> 00:37:27,861
It's like much closer to Sushi Go than it is to Risk.

759
00:37:28,201 --> 00:37:29,962
And that isn't to denigrate Blood Rage.

760
00:37:30,002 --> 00:37:32,384
I think Eric Ling's brilliant and he did a good job with it.

761
00:37:33,264 --> 00:37:35,766
But it can create weird moments

762
00:37:35,826 --> 00:37:37,146
because there are times when like.

763
00:37:37,930 --> 00:37:39,571
you thought you were playing a drafting game,

764
00:37:39,591 --> 00:37:41,812
but then it slides into being a little bit of a war game,

765
00:37:41,852 --> 00:37:44,393
and it feels like not at ease with itself.

766
00:37:44,894 --> 00:37:47,635
Whereas in Inish, you're playing a drafting game,

767
00:37:47,695 --> 00:37:50,117
but the drafting game is entirely about action denial

768
00:37:50,277 --> 00:37:50,937
and about fighting.

769
00:37:52,498 --> 00:37:54,439
So the third thing I think that's very important

770
00:37:54,559 --> 00:37:57,561
is to give players diplomatic flexibility.

771
00:37:59,260 --> 00:38:01,021
There aren't villains in real life.

772
00:38:01,081 --> 00:38:02,782
We have partners and we have adversaries.

773
00:38:02,962 --> 00:38:05,244
And sometimes our partners become our adversaries.

774
00:38:05,484 --> 00:38:09,547
And sometimes we need to find partners

775
00:38:09,727 --> 00:38:10,868
in those who oppose us.

776
00:38:12,089 --> 00:38:14,771
No diplomacy system you design is going to be

777
00:38:14,831 --> 00:38:16,332
as clever as your players.

778
00:38:16,672 --> 00:38:18,133
So you want to try to give them

779
00:38:18,193 --> 00:38:19,934
the most creative framework.

780
00:38:20,679 --> 00:38:21,861
that they could possibly exist in.

781
00:38:21,881 --> 00:38:24,424
I think this is one reason why turn-based strategy games,

782
00:38:25,005 --> 00:38:26,166
especially on the digital side,

783
00:38:26,206 --> 00:38:27,848
really struggle with their diplomacy systems.

784
00:38:27,928 --> 00:38:31,372
It's just hard to create the sort of freewheeling

785
00:38:31,793 --> 00:38:35,678
deal-making that you see in a game like diplomacy

786
00:38:35,838 --> 00:38:37,560
in a digital space.

787
00:38:40,843 --> 00:38:44,905
The last takeaway is I think the most complicated one,

788
00:38:44,965 --> 00:38:47,667
and it's the one that I'm the most unsure of personally.

789
00:38:48,087 --> 00:38:50,288
And this has to do with the management of hope

790
00:38:50,849 --> 00:38:51,529
and of victory.

791
00:38:51,949 --> 00:38:54,491
So victory conditions I think are the most critical element

792
00:38:54,591 --> 00:38:55,631
of any game design.

793
00:38:56,512 --> 00:38:58,653
In my own practice, they are the very first thing

794
00:38:58,953 --> 00:39:02,615
that I put to page, and they are the last thing

795
00:39:02,635 --> 00:39:03,896
that I ever want to tamper with.

796
00:39:04,677 --> 00:39:07,278
The victory conditions put everybody together.

797
00:39:07,458 --> 00:39:08,478
They're like the script.

798
00:39:08,578 --> 00:39:09,979
Even more than the rest of the rules,

799
00:39:10,039 --> 00:39:12,419
the victory conditions bind the players together.

800
00:39:13,020 --> 00:39:15,641
But you run into a problem once another player can't win.

801
00:39:16,241 --> 00:39:19,242
And here I often think of Martin Wallace's 2001 game,

802
00:39:19,282 --> 00:39:19,582
Liberté.

803
00:39:19,602 --> 00:39:22,283
One of the things that's great about Wallace titles

804
00:39:22,603 --> 00:39:25,424
is I feel like he must design very quickly because he

805
00:39:25,464 --> 00:39:26,645
doesn't cover his tracks.

806
00:39:27,185 --> 00:39:31,346
You can sort of see all of the development in the game just by looking at the final game.

807
00:39:31,786 --> 00:39:33,786
And so Liberté is a game about the French Revolution.

808
00:39:33,846 --> 00:39:35,007
It's an election game.

809
00:39:35,507 --> 00:39:40,028
But the way the math of the elections works out, certain factions, certain players are

810
00:39:40,048 --> 00:39:41,188
always going to be like way ahead.

811
00:39:41,668 --> 00:39:44,509
Like after the first election, a couple of players are going to win like eight points

812
00:39:44,589 --> 00:39:46,629
and then every, you can even see it in the screenshot actually.

813
00:39:46,949 --> 00:39:49,970
Like those two people did very well and everyone else is just dead last.

814
00:39:50,490 --> 00:39:51,530
And this will always happen.

815
00:39:51,830 --> 00:39:53,010
This isn't like bad play.

816
00:39:53,311 --> 00:39:54,972
And in fact, in the next election,

817
00:39:55,052 --> 00:39:56,533
those people who are ahead, they're

818
00:39:56,553 --> 00:39:57,773
going to get more ahead.

819
00:39:58,594 --> 00:39:59,855
And the way Wallace dealt with this,

820
00:39:59,895 --> 00:40:02,536
instead of fixing the kind of core math problem that

821
00:40:02,556 --> 00:40:06,279
was producing this result, is he created two alternate victory

822
00:40:06,319 --> 00:40:09,000
conditions, misery conditions, or what they're actually

823
00:40:09,020 --> 00:40:11,842
called, whereby the players who are losing

824
00:40:12,002 --> 00:40:13,483
can kind of flip the table over.

825
00:40:13,643 --> 00:40:15,424
And they have totally different ways of winning

826
00:40:16,225 --> 00:40:18,006
that are so dangerous you would never do it

827
00:40:18,166 --> 00:40:20,708
unless there was no chance you were going to win by points.

828
00:40:21,348 --> 00:40:24,651
And what this does is even until the very, very last moment,

829
00:40:25,312 --> 00:40:27,894
all players remain kind of in the game.

830
00:40:28,715 --> 00:40:31,297
Now, this to me is a very good idea,

831
00:40:31,317 --> 00:40:34,420
and I like it, and I build alternate victory conditions

832
00:40:34,480 --> 00:40:36,021
in almost every game that I've worked on.

833
00:40:36,562 --> 00:40:39,805
But I wonder too, if there's another way

834
00:40:39,825 --> 00:40:43,248
of thinking about victory that isn't so straightjacketed.

835
00:40:45,775 --> 00:40:48,196
have to think about the games of Phil Eklund.

836
00:40:48,777 --> 00:40:50,457
Because the thing about Phil Eklund's games,

837
00:40:50,678 --> 00:40:52,579
they're immensely complicated and goofy

838
00:40:52,659 --> 00:40:54,780
and they're extremely random and mean.

839
00:40:55,280 --> 00:40:57,081
So this is a shot from High Frontier.

840
00:40:58,142 --> 00:40:59,783
If you can believe it, this is like 1 20th

841
00:41:00,503 --> 00:41:01,524
of what the board looks like.

842
00:41:02,184 --> 00:41:04,005
And it is that complicated all the way through.

843
00:41:04,912 --> 00:41:10,556
And in High Frontier, I once spent an hour planning a mission to one of Jupiter's moons,

844
00:41:10,756 --> 00:41:16,060
and then the mission was about halfway through and I hit a radiation belt wrong, and one

845
00:41:16,080 --> 00:41:21,284
of my spaceship components blew up, and I spent the next hour, like hour of game time,

846
00:41:21,604 --> 00:41:26,188
attempting to rescue my poor astronauts who were drifting to one Lagrange point or another.

847
00:41:27,571 --> 00:41:28,291
And it was great.

848
00:41:28,892 --> 00:41:31,773
And there's this amazing thing about Eklund's games

849
00:41:31,953 --> 00:41:36,276
where the story that the game is telling is so bracing,

850
00:41:36,336 --> 00:41:39,438
is so powerful, that even when you're out of condition,

851
00:41:39,858 --> 00:41:43,900
out of contention for victory, you don't want to unplug.

852
00:41:44,020 --> 00:41:45,601
You don't wanna un-immerse yourself.

853
00:41:45,641 --> 00:41:46,822
And this is what usually happens.

854
00:41:47,102 --> 00:41:48,683
If the victory condition is the only thing

855
00:41:49,063 --> 00:41:50,464
that is immersing your players,

856
00:41:50,884 --> 00:41:52,285
then you need to create a system

857
00:41:52,305 --> 00:41:54,106
where the players always have a chance to win.

858
00:41:54,686 --> 00:41:56,668
But if the other storytelling techniques

859
00:41:57,148 --> 00:41:59,410
are giving them something, then the victory condition

860
00:41:59,470 --> 00:42:01,792
starts to be a little less important.

861
00:42:03,393 --> 00:42:06,176
So I want to close with a short quota,

862
00:42:06,196 --> 00:42:08,197
and then we'll have about 15 minutes for questions,

863
00:42:09,418 --> 00:42:11,240
which is to talk a little bit about video games,

864
00:42:11,460 --> 00:42:13,942
since this is primarily a video game design conference.

865
00:42:14,442 --> 00:42:16,564
So one of the funny things is that the space

866
00:42:16,584 --> 00:42:19,206
that I work in in design, these multilateral conflict games,

867
00:42:19,587 --> 00:42:20,828
video games are really bad at them.

868
00:42:21,108 --> 00:42:21,728
Like, horrible.

869
00:42:21,768 --> 00:42:25,510
Like, if you've ever played a game of StarCraft in the free-for-all mode, I'm just sorry.

870
00:42:26,090 --> 00:42:27,991
Because the games just aren't designed for it.

871
00:42:28,031 --> 00:42:32,952
I mean, even multiplayer competitive games, if you think about something like Dota or

872
00:42:32,992 --> 00:42:37,494
any of the other MOBAs, I mean, or Counter-Strike, these are 5v5s, these are team sports.

873
00:42:38,975 --> 00:42:43,657
In terms of the actual game theory, we're talking about formally two-player games, even

874
00:42:43,697 --> 00:42:45,617
if they have multiple humans involved.

875
00:42:46,037 --> 00:42:48,438
Or cooperative experiences, something like Overcooked.

876
00:42:49,857 --> 00:42:53,899
Games just really aren't, digital games, they have a hard time with the free-for-all game,

877
00:42:54,580 --> 00:43:00,583
with the exception of something that's happened in the past couple years, which is to say the rise of the Battle Royale.

878
00:43:02,384 --> 00:43:09,687
I think that these are the most important games that have been developed since Minecraft, and probably even maybe more important because they are truly

879
00:43:10,228 --> 00:43:17,832
multilateral conflict games, and even if you hate them, if you've played them, you probably have memories from the games you have played.

880
00:43:18,272 --> 00:43:20,274
You've played games where you've randomly died,

881
00:43:20,294 --> 00:43:23,397
and then the rest of your squad has attempted to avenge you

882
00:43:23,477 --> 00:43:26,120
as they hunted your killer over the battlefield.

883
00:43:26,360 --> 00:43:28,002
And you watched them with rapt attention

884
00:43:28,022 --> 00:43:29,363
because even though your character was dead,

885
00:43:29,824 --> 00:43:30,985
you were still in the game.

886
00:43:31,766 --> 00:43:34,649
They have amazing storytelling capacity.

887
00:43:34,689 --> 00:43:36,771
When we talk about open world games, we usually...

888
00:43:37,779 --> 00:43:42,042
are not talking about open world so much as a very full world,

889
00:43:42,102 --> 00:43:43,903
where every nook and cranny of a setting

890
00:43:43,943 --> 00:43:47,125
has all these little side plots and branching narratives in it.

891
00:43:47,746 --> 00:43:49,647
For my money, the Battle Royale games

892
00:43:49,687 --> 00:43:51,789
are the only true open world games out there,

893
00:43:52,289 --> 00:43:54,891
because it's really emergent what can happen.

894
00:43:54,951 --> 00:43:56,653
You have no idea the kind of story

895
00:43:56,673 --> 00:43:58,914
that each match is going to tell, outside of the fact

896
00:43:58,934 --> 00:44:01,056
that you need to spend your first 10 minutes feverishly

897
00:44:01,136 --> 00:44:02,717
looting before you get shot.

898
00:44:05,133 --> 00:44:09,357
And, you know, I've been talking mostly about storytelling and not so much like mechanisms

899
00:44:09,397 --> 00:44:12,541
and strategy, although we can go into that in the Q&A if you'd like, but one thing I

900
00:44:12,581 --> 00:44:18,026
will say is these games also produce really interesting strategic concerns.

901
00:44:18,847 --> 00:44:23,913
If you are on, you know, a hill watching the last two squads, or maybe the last two squads,

902
00:44:23,993 --> 00:44:25,314
fight and exhaust themselves...

903
00:44:26,274 --> 00:44:28,235
you might want to intervene and get that loot.

904
00:44:28,755 --> 00:44:30,416
But if you fire your weapons, you

905
00:44:30,496 --> 00:44:33,077
might telegraph your position to those squads

906
00:44:33,137 --> 00:44:34,937
or to another squad that might be watching you.

907
00:44:35,477 --> 00:44:38,919
There are all these concerns about position, exposure,

908
00:44:38,959 --> 00:44:39,639
and supply.

909
00:44:39,959 --> 00:44:42,080
These are really interesting strategic concerns

910
00:44:42,600 --> 00:44:44,621
that are only made possible because we're dealing

911
00:44:44,661 --> 00:44:46,321
with a multilateral conflict.

912
00:44:46,922 --> 00:44:52,086
So in short, I think that by looking at games which are about kingmaking and which really,

913
00:44:52,266 --> 00:44:58,391
frankly, address problems of multiplayer and rather address problems of the multilateral

914
00:45:00,192 --> 00:45:01,593
Let me start that over.

915
00:45:01,993 --> 00:45:07,058
So in short, what I'm trying to say is, basically, designs that feature high player interaction,

916
00:45:07,078 --> 00:45:11,683
that feature multilateral conflict, I think they've got big storytelling payoffs that

917
00:45:11,723 --> 00:45:15,686
are worth investigating, and I also think that they also have big strategic payoffs.

918
00:45:16,447 --> 00:45:20,831
And there's a whole world of different sorts of designs that we just sort of need to explore,

919
00:45:20,871 --> 00:45:25,415
but part of that is realizing our own assumptions about the kind of games that we value.

920
00:45:26,444 --> 00:45:28,225
deciding whether or not we might wanna challenge

921
00:45:28,245 --> 00:45:29,126
some of those assumptions.

922
00:45:29,626 --> 00:45:30,387
All right, thank you guys.

923
00:45:37,251 --> 00:45:38,532
